PR:PROJECT_SUMMARY               	Krabbe disease (KD) is caused by mutations in the galactosylceramidase (GALC)
PR:PROJECT_SUMMARY               	gene, which encodes a lysosomal enzyme that degrades galactolipids, including
PR:PROJECT_SUMMARY               	galactosylceramide and galactosylsphingosine (psychosine). GALC deficiency
PR:PROJECT_SUMMARY               	results in progressive intracellular accumulation of psychosine, which is
PR:PROJECT_SUMMARY               	believed to be the main cause for the demyelinating neurodegeneration in KD
PR:PROJECT_SUMMARY               	pathology. Umbilical cord blood transplantation slows disease progression if
PR:PROJECT_SUMMARY               	performed presymptomatically, but carries a significant risk of morbidity and
PR:PROJECT_SUMMARY               	mortality. Accurate presymptomatic diagnosis is therefore critical to facilitate
PR:PROJECT_SUMMARY               	the efficacy of existing transplant approaches and avoid unnecessary treatment
PR:PROJECT_SUMMARY               	of children who will not develop KD. Unfortunately current diagnostic criteria,
PR:PROJECT_SUMMARY               	including GALC activity, genetic analysis, and psychosine measurement, are
PR:PROJECT_SUMMARY               	insufficient for secure presymptomatic diagnosis. Herein, we performed a global
PR:PROJECT_SUMMARY               	metabolomic analysis to identify pathogenetic metabolic pathways and novel
PR:PROJECT_SUMMARY               	biomarkers implicated in the authentic mouse model of KD, twitcher. At a time
PR:PROJECT_SUMMARY               	point before onset of signs of disease, twitcher hindbrains had metabolic
PR:PROJECT_SUMMARY               	profiles similar to wild type, with the exception of a decrease in metabolites
PR:PROJECT_SUMMARY               	related to glucose energy metabolism. Instead, many metabolic pathways were
PR:PROJECT_SUMMARY               	altered after early signs of disease in the twitcher, including decreased
PR:PROJECT_SUMMARY               	phospholipid turnover, restricted mitochondrial metabolism of branched-chain
PR:PROJECT_SUMMARY               	amino acids, increased inflammation, neurotransmitter metabolism and osmolytes.
PR:PROJECT_SUMMARY               	Hypoxanthine, a purine derivative, is increased before signs of disease appear,
PR:PROJECT_SUMMARY               	suggesting its potential as a biomarker for early diagnosis of KD. Additionally,
PR:PROJECT_SUMMARY               	given the early changes in glucose metabolism in the pathogenesis of KD,
PR:PROJECT_SUMMARY               	diagnostic modalities that report metabolic function, such as positron emission
PR:PROJECT_SUMMARY               	tomography, may be useful in KD.
